The legal fight over the Trump administration rule requiring hospitals to publicly list their prices and the discounts they give insurance companies is testing the bounds of free speech protections.
Health-care industry groups and two private hospitals are using the First Amendment to try and block the Department of Health and Human Services rule before it takes effect in January 2021.
But some health scholars say patients, particularly those willing to shop around for medical services, aren’t stupid.
Other health scholars counter that not every patient knows how much of their deductible they’ve spent and neither do hospitals.
The 2010 Affordable Care Act amended the 1944 Public Health Service Act to require all hospitals to disclose their standard charges for the items and services they provide.